      "time": "~20s",
      "narrative": "- I want to show this from the seller's point of view. The story starts where developers already work: GitHub.\n- Instead of asking teams to adopt a separate AI tool for every task, GitHub Copilot app brings the work to one front door.\n- That matters because the repo is where the issue, the code, the review, and the path to production already come together.",
      "demo_actions": "- Start on the GitHub Copilot app home screen.\n- Point out this is a native GitHub experience.\n- Briefly frame the app as the starting point for issue, prompt, or PR based work.",
      "screenshot": null
    },
    {
      "locked": false,
      "locks": {
        "time": false,
        "narrative": false,
        "demo_actions": false,
        "screenshot": false,
        "visual": false,
        "design_plan": false
      },
      "time": "~40s",
      "narrative": "- Here, I can start from an issue already in GitHub. That is the key message for this audience: we are meeting the developer in the repo, not pulling them into a disconnected tool.\n- The app has the context that matters right away: code, issues, pull requests, and search.\n- So the conversation begins with native context, not manual setup.",
      "demo_actions": "- Open or highlight an issue in the app.\n- Start a session from that issue.\n- Show the session workspace with files, branch, and conversation visible.",
      "screenshot": null
    },
    {
      "locked": false,
      "locks": {
        "time": false,
        "narrative": false,
        "demo_actions": false,
        "screenshot": false,
        "visual": false,
        "design_plan": false
      },
      "time": "~40s",
      "narrative": "- From this same front door, the developer can move across the tools they already use.\n- If they want to stay in the desktop app, they can inspect changes, run checks, preview the result, and move toward a pull request.\n- If they want the terminal, the SDK, or VS Code, GitHub Copilot is still the anchor. The experience stays connected instead of fragmenting across separate products.",
      "demo_actions": "- Show the built-in workspace areas for diffs, browser preview, and terminal checks.\n- Verbally call out CLI, SDK, and VS Code as connected paths from the same Copilot entry point.\n- Keep this high level rather than deep technical clicks.",
      "screenshot": null
    },
    {
      "locked": false,
      "locks": {
        "time": false,
        "narrative": false,
        "demo_actions": false,
        "screenshot": false,
        "visual": false,
        "design_plan": false
      },
      "time": "~45s",
      "narrative": "- This is where the competitive point lands.\n- Competitors tend to win one surface. Maybe the editor. Maybe the model. Maybe a terminal experience.\n- GitHub gives us the broader system. One place to start, with connected paths into coding, validation, review, and merge.\n- That is a better story for customers because it reduces tool sprawl and keeps teams working in the flow they already trust.",
      "demo_actions": "- Return to the session overview.\n- Point to review and merge steps in the app.\n- Use the visual state of one workspace to reinforce connected lifecycle coverage.",
      "screenshot": null
    },
    {
      "locked": false,
      "locks": {
        "time": false,
        "narrative": false,
        "demo_actions": false,
        "screenshot": false,
        "visual": false,
        "design_plan": false
      },
      "time": "~35s",
      "narrative": "- And the ecosystem keeps extending.\n- Custom skills can sync across sessions. External data can connect through MCP servers. And this front door can reach beyond coding tools into the broader Microsoft stack, including Azure AI Foundry when customers need model choice and governed AI at scale.\n- So when sellers hear point tools, the response is simple: GitHub is where developers start, and from there the rest of the ecosystem is already connected.",
      "demo_actions": "- Briefly point out customization or skills settings if available.\n- Verbally mention MCP connections and Azure AI Foundry as part of the broader connected ecosystem.\n- End on a clean overview screen.",
      "screenshot": null
    }
